ssociate Reformed Presbyterian]]<ref name=FPC>[http://www.firstprescola.com/590634 First Presbyterian of Columbia history page]</ref>\n|allegiance  = {{flag|United States}}\n|branch      = [[File:United States Department of the Army Seal.svg|15px]] [[United States Army]]\n|serviceyears=1972-2003<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ausa.org/legislation/congressionalinfo/Documents/OAS%20112th%20Congress.pdf |title=Once a Soldier... Always a Soldier |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |year=2011 |work=Legislative Agenda |publisher=[[Association of the United States Army]] |accessdate=January 28, 2013}}</ref>\n|rank        = [[File:US-O6 insignia.svg|15px]] [[Colonel (United States)|Colonel]]\n|unit        = [[United States Army Reserve]] (1972-1975)<br>[[South Carolina Army National Guard]] (1975-2003)\n|website     = [http://www.joewilson.house.gov joewilson.house.gov]\n}}\n'''Addison Graves \"Joe\" Wilson, Sr.''' (born July 31, 1947) is the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|SC|2}}, serving since 2001.  The district stretches from the state capital, [[Columbia, South Carolina|Columbia]], to the Georgia-South Carolina border.  He is a member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]]. He previously served in the [[South Carolina Senate]] from 1985 to 2001.\n\nHe is a member of the [[Steering and Policy Committee of the United States House of Representatives|House Republican Policy Committee]] and is an Assistant Republican [[Whip (politics)|Whip]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.joewilson.house.gov/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=37&Itemid=34 |title=Joe Wilson \u2013 Congressman Joe Wilson's Biography |publisher=Joewilson.house.gov |date=July 31, 1947 |accessdate=December 8, 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2009, Wilson received international attention when he interrupted a [[Barack Obama speech to joint session of Congress, September 2009|speech by U.S. President Barack Obama]] to the joint session of Congress by shouting \"You lie!\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2009/POLITICS/09/09/joe.wilson/index.html |title=CNN, Politics, retrieved 14 September 2009 |publisher=Cnn.com |date=September 10, 2009 |accessdate=September 16, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.aljazeera.net/news/americas/2009/09/2009916172057802997.html |title=Carter: Obama a target for racism |publisher=English.aljazeera.net |date=20\n09-09-16 |accessdate=October 7, 2010}}</ref> The incident resulted in a formal rebuke by the House of Representatives largely along party lines.<ref name=nyt20090915>{{cite news|last=Phillips |first=Kate |url=http://thecaucus.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/09/15/blogging-the-house-action-on-wilson/ |title=House Admonishes Wilson on Outburst|newspaper=The New York Times|date=September 9, 2009 |accessdate=August 22, 2011}}</ref>\n\nWilson was re-elected in 2010 by a comfortable 9 percentage points over his nearest challenger and when he ran unopposed in the  2012 general election he was re-elected with 96% of the vote.\n\n==Early life, education and career==\n[[File:US Navy 070625-N-3642E-582 Sgt. Matt Piano briefs the safety procedure to firing a M136 AT4 to the Secretary of the Navy (SECNAV) The Honorable Dr. Donald C. Winter and Rep. Joe Wilson, left, 2nd South Carolina Congressional Di.jpg|thumb|left|Joe Wilson, in red shirt at left]]\nWilson was born in [[Charleston, South Carolina]], the son of Wray (n\u00e9e Graves) and Hugh deVeaux Wilson.<ref>http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~battle/reps/wilsonjoe.htm</ref> Wilson obtained a bachelor's degree in political science from [[Washington and Lee University]] in 1969 where he joined [[Sigma Nu]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sigmanu.wlu.edu/famousalum.html}}</ref> and obtained his [[Juris Doctor]] ([[Juris Doctor|J.D.]]) degree from the [[University of South Carolina School of Law]] in 1972.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://projects.washingtonpost.com/congress/members/w000795/ |title=Joe Wilson &#124; Congressional votes database |publisher=Projects.washingtonpost.com |date= |accessdate=December 8, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Joe Wilson's Biography|url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/biography/3985/joe-wilson-sr#.VIdSRDHF-Tt|website=Project Vote Smart|accessdate=9 December 2014}}</ref> From 1972 to 1975, Wilson served in the [[United States Army Reserve]], and then as a Staff Judge Advocate in the [[South Carolina Army National Guard]] assigned to the [[218th Maneuver Enhancement Brigade (United States)|218th Mechanized Infantry Brigade]] until retiring from military service as a [[Colonel (United States)|colonel]] in 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.joewilson.house.gov/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=37&Itemid=40 |title=Joe Wilson \u2013 Congressman Joe Wilson's Biography |publisher=Joewilson.house.gov |date=July 31, 1947 |accessdate=December 8, 2009}}</ref>\n\nWilson was active in South Carolina Republican politics from a young age, participating in his first Republican campaign in 1962. As a teenager he joined the campaign of [[United States House of Representatives|Congressman]] [[Floyd Spence]], later working as an aide to [[United States Senate|Senator]] [[Strom Thurmond]].\n\nAs a real estate attorney, Wilson co-accounted the law firm Kirkland, Wilson, Moore, Taylor & Thomas<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.votesmart.org/bio.php?can_id=3985 |title=Project Vote Smart \u2013 Representative Addison Graves 'Joe' Wilson Sr. \u2013 Biography |publisher=Votesmart.org |date=July 31, 1947 |accessdate=September 16, 2009}}</ref> in [[West Columbia, South Carolina|West Columbia]], where he practiced for over 25 years. Wilson was also a municipal judge in [[Springdale, Lexington County, South Carolina|Springdale, South Carolina]].<ref name=\"ourcampaigns\">{{cite web|title=\nWilson, Addison Graves \"Joe\" |url= http://www.ourcampaigns.com/CandidateDetail.html?CandidateID=2083 |date= September 10, 2009 |publisher= Our Campaigns |accessdate=September 12, 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn 1981 and 1982, during the first term of the [[Reagan Administration]], Wilson served as deputy general counsel for former Governor [[James B. Edwards|Jim Edwards]] at the [[U.S. Department of Energy]]. Wilson is also a graduate of Morton Blackwell's [[Leadership Institute]] in Arlington, Virginia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenation.com/blog/right-goes-viral |title=The Right Goes Viral |publisher=The Nation |date=October 21, 2009 |accessdate=October 7, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==South Carolina Senate==\nWilson was elected to the [[South Carolina Senate]] in 1984 as a Republican from [[Lexington County, South Carolina|Lexington County]]. He was re-elected four times, the last three times unopposed; Lexington County is one of the most Republican counties in the state. He never missed a regular legislative session in 17 years. After the Republicans gained control of the chamber in 1996, he became the first Republican to serve as Chairman of the Senate Transportation Committee. Wilson was a member of the [[Columbia College (Columbia, South Carolina)|Columbia College]] Board of Visitors and [[Coker College]] Board of Trustees.\n\nDuring his tenure in the South Carolina Senate, Wilson was the primary sponsor of bills which included the following: establishing a National Guard license plate,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scstatehouse.gov/sess113_1999-2000/bills/150.htm |title=South Carolina General Assembly Bill S0150 |publisher=Scstatehouse.gov |date= |accessdate=September 16, 2009}}</ref> providing paid leave for state employees to perform disaster relief services,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scstatehouse.gov/sess113_1999-2000/bills/283.htm |title=South Carolina General Assembly Bill S0283 |publisher=Scstatehouse.gov |date= |accessdate=September 16, 2009}}</ref> and requiring men aged 18\u201326 to register for the [[Selective Service System]] when applying for a driver's license.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scstatehouse.gov/sess114_2001-2002/bills/634.htm |title=South Carolina General Assembly Bill S0634 |publisher=Scstatehouse.gov |date= |accessdate=September 16, 2009}}</ref> In 2000, Wilson was one of seven senators who voted against removing the [[Flags of the Confederate States of America#Battle flag|Confederate battle flag]] from being displayed over the state house.<ref>{{cite web | title = Rep. Joe Wilson said \"the Confederate heritage is very honorable\" during SC flag dispute | work = Facing South | publisher = The Institute for Southern Studies | url = http://www.southernstudies.org/2009/09/rep-joe-wilson-said-the-confederate-heritage-is-very-honorable-in-1999.html | accessdate = September 11, 2009}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Committee assignments===\n[[File:Joe Wilson, official photo portrait, color.jpg|thumb|right|Official House photo portrait, 2006]]As of the [[113th United States Congress|113th Congress]], Wilson serves on three [[standing committees]] and various subcommittees overseeing specific areas of legislation. Wilson serves on the [[United States House Committee on Armed Services|Committee on Armed Services]] and is Chairman of the [[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Military Personnel|Subcommittee on Military Personnel]];<ref>{{cite web |title=Armed Services Committee \u2013 Military Personnel |url=http://armedservices.house.gov/index.cfm/military-personnel |work=house.gov |publisher=House Armed Services Committee |date=January 13, 2013 |accessdate=June 5, 2013}}</ref> he also serves on the [[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Strategic Forces|Subcommittee on Strategic Forces]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Armed Services Committee \u2013 Strategic Forces |url=http://armedservices.house.gov/index.cfm/strategic-forces |work=house.gov |publisher=House Armed Services Committee |date=January 13, 2013 |accessdate=June 5, 2013}}</ref> He serves on the [[United States House Committee on Education and the Workforce|Committee on Education and the Workforce]], for which he also is a member of the [[United States House Education Subcommittee on Health, Employment, Labor, and Pensions|Subcommittee on Health, Employment, Labor, and Pensions]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Members, Subcommittees & Jurisdictions |url=http://edworkforce.house.gov/committee/subcommitteesjurisdictions.htm |work=house.gov |publisher=Education & the Workforce Committee |date= |accessdate=June 5, 2013}}</ref> As a member of the [[United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs|Committee on Foreign Affairs]], Wilson serves on the [[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on Europe|Subcommittee on Europe]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Subcommittee on Europe |url=http://www.internationalrelations.house.gov/subcommittees.asp?committee=4 |work=house.gov |publisher=United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs |date= |accessdate=September 28, 2009}}</ref> and [[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on the Middle East and South Asia|Subcommittee on the Middle East and South Asia]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Subcommittee on the Middle East and South Asia |url=http://www.internationalrelations.house.gov/subcommittees.asp?committee=7 |work=house.gov |publisher=United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs |date= |accessdate=September 28, 2009}}</ref> Wilson is a member of the [[Republican Study Committee]] and the [[Tea Party Caucus]].\n\n===Caucus memberships===\n*Composites Caucus (Co-Chair)\n*Diabetes Caucus\n*Global Health Caucus\n*India Caucus\n*[[United States Congressional International Conservation Caucus|International Conservation Caucus]]\n*Israel Allies Caucus\n*Russia Democracy Caucus\n*Sportsmen's Caucus\n*[[Steering and Policy Committee of the United States House of Representatives|House Republican Policy Committee]]\n*[[Tea Party Caucus]]\n*Congressional Arts Caucus\n\nLike his former boss, Spence, Wilson is an ardent social and fiscal conservative, and a strong supporter of the military.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.votesmart.org/issue_rating_category.php?can_id=BS021931 |title=Project Vote Smart \u2013 Representative Addison Graves 'Joe' Wilson, Sr. \u2013 Interest Group Ratings |publisher=Votesmart.org |date=December 18, 2001 |accessdate=December 8, 2009}}</ref> He is a member of the [[Republican Study Committee]].\n\nIn 2003, Wilson voted for the [[Medicare Prescription Drug, Improvement, and Modernization Act]], including its Section 1011 authorizing $250,000 annually of taxpayer money to reimburse hospitals for treatment of illegal immigrants. In 2009, Wilson changed to his current position opposing public funds for healthcare of illegal immigrants.<ref>{{cite web |last= Shaw |first= Donny |title= Joe Wilson Voted to Provide Taxpayer Money for Illegal Immigrants' Healthcare |url= http://www.opencongress.org/articles/view/1219-Joe-Wilson-Voted-to-Provide-Taxpayer-Money-for-Illegal-Immigrants-Healthcare |date= September 11, 2009 |publisher= OpenCongress,org |accessdate=September 12, 2009}}</ref> In the 2006 elections, he defeated Ellisor again, gaining 62.7 percent of the vote, and kept his House seat.<ref>Wilson received 127,811 votes to Ellisor's 76,090 votes, with 151 write-ins. See [http://www.scvotes.org/statistics/election_returns_from_primaries_and_general_elections_statewide South Carolina Election Commission official web site, go to the page for November 7, 2006 general election]. Retrieved April 10, 2008.</ref> In the 2008 general election, he won 54 percent of the vote to [[Rob Miller (South Carolina politician)|Rob Miller]]'s 46 percent,<ref>{{cite news |title= U.S. House |newspaper= [[USA Today]] |page= A16|date= November 5, 2008 |accessdate=September 10, 2009}}</ref> the closest race in the district in 20 years.\n\n===Legislation===\nWilson has sponsored and co-sponsored a number of [[bill (proposed law)|bill]]s, concerning teacher recruitment and retention, college campus fire safety, National Guard troop levels, arming airline pilots, tax credits for adoptions, tax credits for living organ donors, and state defense forces.\n\nAs of January 2006, eight bills co-sponsored by Wilson have passed the House,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/person.xpd?id=400433 |title=Addison (Joe) Wilson |date= |work=GovTrack.us |publisher= |accessdate=November 2, 2009 }}</ref> including H.R. 1973, the Senator Paul Simon Water for the Poor Act of 2005, making safe water and sanitation an objective of U.S. assistance to developing countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/bdquery/z?d109:HR01973:@@@P: |title=Thomas (Library of Congress): H.R. 1973 |publisher=Thomas.loc.gov |date= |accessdate=September 16, 2009}}</ref>\n\nWilson is a staunch advocate of a federal prohibition of online [[poker]]. In 2006, he co-sponsored H.R. 4411, the [[Goodlatte]]-Leach Internet Gambling Prohibition Act<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/bdquery/z?d109:h.r.04411: |title=Thomas (Library of Congress): HR 4411 |publisher=Thomas.loc.gov |date= |accessdate=September 16, 2009}}</ref> and H.R. 4777, the Internet Gambling Prohibition Act.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/bdquery/z?d109:h.r.04777: |title=Thomas (Library of Congress): HR 4777 |publisher=Thomas.loc.gov |date= |accessdate=September 16, 2009}}</ref>\n\nHe has cited as one of his proudest congressional achievements the Drafting Business Expensing Act of 2003{{Citation needed|date=September 2011}}, which allows businesses to immediately write-off fifty percent of the cost of business equipment and machinery. This bonus [[depreciation]] provision has been extended for 2008 and 2009 in two separate stimulus bills.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/PLAW-110publ185/content-detail.html |title=Public Law 110-185 \u2013 Economic Stimulus Act of 2008 |date=February 13, 2008 |work= |publisher=gpo.gov |accessdate=November 21, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.whitehouse.gov/assets/documents/Public_Law-111-5.pdf |title=PUBLIC LAW 111\u20135\u2014 |date=February 17, 2009 |work= |publisher=whitehouse.gov |accessdate=November 21, 2009}}</ref> In addition, Wilson spearheaded the Drafting Teacher Recruitment and Retention Act of 2003, which offers higher education loan forgiveness to math, science and special education teachers in schools with a predominantly low income student population.<ref name=\"statebio\">James Rosen, [http://www.thestate.com/news-extras/story/936307.html \"Joe Wilson Biography\"],\n\n''[[The State (newspaper)|The State]]'', September 10, 2009</ref> He cites as his most important vote the [[Jobs and Growth Tax Relief Reconciliation Act of 2003]].<ref name=\"statebio\"/>\n\n===Outburst during 2009 Presidential address===\n[[File:Joe Wilson's You Lie interruption.theora.ogv|thumb|Wilson's interruption of President Obama's address (at 00:15)]]\nOn September 9, 2009, Wilson shouted at President [[Barack Obama]] while Obama [[Barack Obama speech to joint session of Congress, September 2009|addressed a joint session of Congress]] to outline his proposal for [[Health care reform in the United States|reforming health care]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2009/sep/10/you-lie-joe-wilson-obama-speech| author=Batty, David |title='You lie': Republican Joe Wilson's outburst at Obama health speech  |date=September 10, 2009 |accessdate=June 3, 2013|newspaper=The Guardian |location=London}}</ref> During his address, Obama said: \"There are also those who claim that our reform effort will insure illegal immigrants. This, too, is false \u2013 the reforms I'm proposing would not apply to those who are here illegally.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2009/09/10/us/politics/10obama.text.html?pagewanted=print |title=Obama's Health Care Speech to Congress |date=September 9, 2009 |publisher=New York Times | accessdate=May 6, 2010}}</ref>  In a breach of [[decorum]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Wilson Apologizes After Accusing Obama of a \u2018Lie\u2019 |url=http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601103&sid=aJTZYsFoY1UQ|agency=Bloomberg |date= September 10, 2009|accessdate=September 10, 2009 |language=|quote=|archiveurl=|archivedate=}}</ref> Wilson pointed at Obama and shouted, \"You lie!\" twice.<ref>{{cite news|title=Obama heckled by GOP during speech to Congress|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20090921140953/http://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5gTWB1M9VPOte4M77spW7Z62NsGyQD9AK4ULO0|agency=Associated Press |date= September 10, 2009|accessdate=September 10, 2009}}</ref><ref>[http://www.politico.com/blogs/bensmith/0909/A_voice_from_the_floor_on_illegal_immigrants_Lie.html Politico:\"A voice from the floor on illegal immigrants: 'Lie'\"]. Retrieved September 9, 2009.</ref><ref>[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2009/09/09/gop-rep-wilson-yells-out_n_281480.html \"The Huffington Post: \"GOP Rep Joe Wilson Yells Out \"Lie\" During Obama Health Care Speech To Congress (VIDEO)\"]. Retrieved September 9, 2009.</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Alex|last=Spillius|title=Barack Obama health care speech: Republican calls president a liar|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/northamerica/usa/6165489/Barack-Obama-health-care-speech-Republican-calls-president-a-liar.html|work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|publisher=|date=September 10, 2009|accessdate=September 9, 2009 | location=London}}</ref> Wilson attracted national and international attention for the incident.<ref>''[[Der Spiegel]]'', [http://www.spiegel.de/politik/ausland/0,1518,648158,00.html Web-Gemeinde schimpft auf Obamas St\u00f6renfried] 10.09.2009 (German), ''[[Le Monde]]'' [http://www.lemonde.fr/archives/article/2009/09/10/reforme-de-la-sante-les-etats-unis-decouvrent-le-combattant-obama_1238389_0.html R\u00e9forme de la sant\u00e9 : les Etats-Unis d\u00e9couvrent le \"combattant\" Obama]. 10.09.09 (French \u2013 dubs him \"Joe 'You Lie' Wilson\"), ''[[El Pa\u00eds]]'', [http://www.elpais.com/articulo/internacional/Obama/Ha/llegado/momento/aprobar/reforma/sanitaria/elpepuint/20090910elpepuint_2/Tes Obama: \"Ha llegado el momento de aprobar la reforma sanitaria\"]. 10.09.09 (Spanish).</ref><ref name=time>''[[Time (magazine)|Time]], September 10, 2009, [http://www.time.com/time/politics/article/0,8599,1921455,00.html \"'You Lie!': Representative Wilson's Outburst\"]</ref> He said afterwards that his outburst reflected his view that the bill would provide government-subsidized benefits to illegal immigrants.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,549243,00.html |title=FOX News coverage of Wilson controversy |publisher=Foxnews.com |date=September 11, 2009 |accessdate=September 16, 2009}}</ref>\n\nThen-White House Chief of Staff [[Rahm Emanuel]] immediately approached senior Republican lawmakers and asked them to identify the heckler and urge him to apologize immediately.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.nytimes.com/2009/09/11/us/politics/11Wilson.html | work=The New York Times | first=Carl | last=Hulse | title=In Lawmaker's Outburst, a Rare Breach of Protocol | date=September 11, 2009}}</ref> Members of Congress from both parties condemned the outburst. \"Totally disrespectful\", said Senator [[John McCain]] (R-[[Arizona]]) of Wilson's utterance. \"No place for it in that setting or any other and he should apologize immediately.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0909/09/lkl.01.html |title=CNN.com \u2013 Transcripts |publisher=Transcripts.cnn.com |date=September 9, 2009 |accessdate=September 16, 2009}}</ref><ref>[http://thedailyvoice.com/voice/2009/09/south-carolina-rep-joe-wilson-002258.php ''The Daily Voice'': \"South Carolina Rep. Joe Wilson calls the President a liar during speech\"]. Retrieved September 9, 2009.</ref> Wilson said later in a statement:<blockquote>This evening I let my emotions get the best of me when listening to the President's remarks regarding the coverage of illegal immigrants in the health care bill. While I disagree with the President's statement, my comments were inappropriate and regrettable. I extend sincere apologies to the President for this lack of civility.<ref>[http://politicalticker.blogs.cnn.com/2009/09/09/wilson-apologizes-i-let-my-emotions-get-the-best-of-me/ \"Wilson apologizes: 'I let my emotions get the best of me'\"]. Retrieved September 9, 2009.</ref></blockquote> Obama later accepted Wilson's apology. \"I'm a big believer that we all make mistakes\", he said. \"He apologized quickly and without equivocation and I'm appreciative of that.\"<ref>{{cite news|last= Stolberg|first= Sheryl Gay|title= Obama Accepts Wilson's Apology|url= http://thecaucus.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/09/10/obama-accepts-wilsons-apology/?hp|date= September 10, 2009 |work= New York Times|accessdate=September 10, 2009}}</ref>\n\n{{Wikisource|Raising a Question of the Privileges of the House|Raising a Question of the Privileges of the House (H. Res. 744)}}\nHouse Democrats called on Wilson to issue a formal apology on the House floor.<ref name=\"reuters-not\">{{cite news|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/domesticNews/idUSTRE58C14N20090913 |title=Lawmaker won't apologize to Obama in Congress &#124; U.S. |agency=Reuters |date=February 9, 2009 |accessdate=September 16, 2009}}</ref> Wilson refused, saying in a televised interview that, \"I believe one apology is sufficient.\"<ref name=\"YouTube-interview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7_dIpZ8XA64 |title=Joe Wilson: 'One Apology Is Sufficient' |publisher=YouTube |date= |accessdate=September 16, 2009}}</ref> Most Congressional Republicans agreed, and opposed further action.<ref>{{cite news |first=Mike |last=Soraghan |authorlink= |title=DeMint: No more apologizing for Wilson |url=http://thehill.com/homenews/house/58423-demint-no-more-apologizing-for-wilson |newspaper=The Hill |publisher= |date=September 12, 2009 |accessdate=September 22, 2009}}</ref> On September 15, the House approved a \"resolution of disapproval\" against Wilson, on a nearly party-line 240\u2013179 vote.<ref>{{cite news |first=Alex |last=Isenstadt |authorlink= |title=House passes resolution of disapproval |url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0909/27194.html |newspaper=Politico |publisher= |date=September 15, 2009 |accessdate=September 15, 2009}}</ref>\n\nSeveral fact-checking organizations wrote that Wilson's views were inaccurate because [[America's Affordable Health Choices Act of 2009|HR 3200]] expressly excludes undocumented aliens from receiving government-subsidized \"affordability credits\".<ref name=\"Obama's Health Care Speech\">{{cite web|url=http://www.factcheck.org/2009/09/obamas-health-care-speech/ |title=Obama's Health Care Speech |publisher=FactCheck.org |date= |accessdate=September 16, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"politifact\">{{cite web|url=http://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2009/sep/09/joe-wilson/joe-wilson-south-carolina-said-obama-lied-he-didnt/ |title=Joe Wilson of South Carolina said Obama lied, but he didn't |publisher=PolitiFact |date= |accessdate=September 16, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://politicalticker.blogs.cnn.com/2009/08/27/cnn-truth-squad-will-health-bill-pay-for-illegal-immigrants-an-update/ |title=CNN Political Ticker: All politics, all the time Blog Archive - CNN Truth Squad: Will health bill pay for illegal immigrants? An update \" - Blogs from CNN.com |publisher=Politicalticker.blogs.cnn.com |date=August 27, 2009 |accessdate=September 16, 2009}}</ref> The non-partisan [[Congressional Research Service]] agreed that people would need to be lawfully present in the U.S. in order to be eligible for the credits, but noted that the bill did not bar non-citizens from buying their own health insurance coverage through the [[health insurance exchange]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cis.org/articles/2009/CRS_Report_on_HR3200.pdf |title=Treatment of Noncitizens in H.R. 3200 |date=August 25, 2009 |work=CRS Report for Congress |publisher=Congressional Research Service |accessdate=November 21, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |authorlink= |title=Republicans Cite Report To Support Illegal Alien Health Care Charge |url=http://www.npr.org/blogs/thetwo-way/2009/09/republicans_cite_report_to_sup.html |date=September 10, 2009 |work=[[National Public Radio]] |accessdate=September 10, 2009}}</ref> The Obama administration said that, in the final bill, illegal immigrants would not be able to participate in the Exchange.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://prescriptions.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/09/11/illegal-immigrants-could-not-buy-insurance-on-new-exchange-white-house-says/|title=Illegal Immigrants Could Not Buy Insurance on New \u2018Exchange,\u2019 White House Says|date=September 11, 2009|accessdate=September 12, 2009|work=The New York Times|author=Herszenhorn, David M.}}</ref> Prior to Obama's speech, Democrats had twice rejected amendments to the bill requiring documentation of legal status in the United States in order to receive benefits under the proposed plan, contending that a more complex application process would delay or prevent citizens from receiving health care.<ref>[http://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20090911/ap_on_go_co/us_health_care_overhaul ]{{dead link|date=August 2010}}</ref> Such language was included in the [[Senate Finance Committee]]'s version of the bill, [[America's Healthy Future Act]].<ref>{{cite web|author=By HealthiNation |url=http://health.yahoo.com/news/ap/us_health_care_overhaul.html |title=News on Yahoo! Health |publisher=Health.yahoo.com |date= |accessdate=August 29, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://edition.cnn.com/2009/POLITICS/09/16/health.care.key.points/ | work=CNN | title=What's in Baucus' health care proposal? | accessdate=May 6, 2010 | date=September 16, 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn contrast to the criticism, many others strongly supported his actions, distrusting that the bill would actually exclude illegal aliens in practice, which allowed Joe Wilson to receive substantial political contributions and gain much notoriety.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/joe-wilsons-you-lie-spurs-support-criticism/ | work=CBS News}}</ref>\n\nFormer President [[Jimmy Carter]] said that the outburst was \"based on [[racism]] ... [t]here is an inherent feeling among many in this country that an [[African-American]] should not be president\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcwashington.com/news/politics/NATL-Jimmy-Carter-Wilsons-Outburst-Was-Racist-59410277.html |title=Jimmy Carter: Wilson's Outburst Was Racist |publisher=NBC |location=Washington |date=September 16, 2009 |accessdate=October 7, 2010}}</ref><ref>Greg Bluestein, Associated Press, [http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2009/sep/15/jimmy-carter-wilsons-cry-based-racism/?feat=home_headlines \"Carter: Wilson's outburst 'based on racism'\"] Washington Times, September 15, 2009</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2009/09/15/jimmy-carter-wilsons-outb_n_288003.html |title=Jimmy Carter: Wilson's Outburst 'Based On Racism' |publisher=Huffington Post |date=September 15, 2009 |accessdate=October 7, 2010 |first=Nick |last=Sabloff}}</ref> and characterized Wilson's act as \"dastardly\".<ref>Greg Bluestein, Associated Press, [http://www.startribune.com/templates/Print_This_Story?sid=59458572 \"Rep. Joe Wilson's son disputes claim by Carter that Congressman's outburst 'based on racism'\"]. Associated Press. September 16, 2009</ref><ref name=\"nydailynews.com\">[http://www.nydailynews.com/news/politics/2009/09/17/2009-09-17_jimmy_carter_gets_flak_for_racism_charge__even_from_white_house.html Jimmy Carter gets flak for racism charge]. NY Daily News.  September 17, 2009</ref> This view was echoed by entertainer and educator [[Bill Cosby]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2009/POLITICS/09/15/carter.obama/index.html |title=\"Carter again cites racism as factor in Obama's treatment\", September 17, 2009 |publisher=CNN |date=September 15, 2009 |accessdate=October 7, 2010}}</ref><ref>[https://www.bet.com/News/Politics_Carter_Repeats_His_Belief_that_Obama_is_Under_Racist_Attack.htm \"Carter Repeats His Belief that Obama is Under Racist Attack\"], bet.com. September 17, 2009</ref> However, others disagreed, including [[Maryland]] representative [[Donna Edwards]], a member of the [[Congressional Black Caucus]].<ref>{{cite web |title='Hardball with Chris Matthews' for Tuesday, September 15, 2009 |url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/32877661/ns/msnbc_tv-hardball_with_chris_matthews/ |work=msnbc.com |date=September 16, 2009 |publisher=MSNBC |accessdate=September 22, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Carter 'Racism' Claim Draws Widespread Criticism |url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2009/09/16/carter-racism-claim-draws-widespread-criticism/ |date=September 16, 2009 |work=FOXNews.com |publisher= |accessdate=September 22, 2009}}</ref> [[Alan Wilson (South Carolina politician)|Alan Wilson]], the Attorney General of South Carolina, said: \"There is not a racist bone in my dad's body. He doesn't even laugh at distasteful jokes.\"<ref name=\"nydailynews.com\"/> [[White House Press Secretary]] [[Robert Gibbs]], when asked about Carter's comments, stated that President Barack Obama \"does not believe that criticism comes based on the color of his skin.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/8260109.stm |title=White House rejects racism claim |publisher=BBC News |date=September 16, 2009 |accessdate=October 7, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/chi-tc-nw-canada-0916-0917sep17,0,5412906.story |title=Gibbs: Racism not basis for opposition |work=Chicago Tribune |date=September 17, 2009 |accessdate=October 7, 2010 |first=Trevor |last=Jensen}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://kdka.com/topstories/jimmy.carter.joe.2.1186411.html |title=Carter: Some Criticism Of Obama Rooted In Racism |publisher=KDKA.com |date=September 16, 2009 |accessdate=October 7, 2010}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the incident, both Wilson and [[Rob Miller (South Carolina politician)|Rob Miller]], his subsequent 2010 general election opponent, experienced a significant upswing in campaign donations. In the week after Wilson's outburst, Miller raised $1.6 million, about three times his 2008 campaign,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.opensecrets.org/races/summary.php?id=SC02&cycle=2008 |title=Congressional Elections: South Carolina District 02 Race: 2008 Cycle |publisher=OpenSecrets |date= |accessdate=September 16, 2009}}</ref> while Wilson raised $1.8 million.<ref>{{cite news |first=Holly |last=Bailey |title=How Joe Wilson's Heckle Became a Campaign Cash Cow |url=http://web.archive.org/web/20100204103320/http://blog.newsweek.com/blogs/thegaggle/archive/2009/09/17/how-joe-wilson-s-heckle-became-a-campaign-cash-cow.aspx |newspaper=Newsweek |date=September 17, 2008 |accessdate=September 17, 2009}}</ref> By September 30, 2009, Wilson had out-paced Miller's fundraising by $2.65 million to $1.69 million respectively.<ref>{{cite web |author=James Rosen |title=Wilson, Miller campaign brings in money from across U.S. |url=http://www.miamiherald.com/692/story/1287522-p2.html |work=Miami Herald |publisher=miamiherald.com |date=October 18, 2009 |accessdate=October 21, 2009}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> This fundraising surge led to Wilson writing fundraising letters for the [[Republican Party of Virginia]]<ref>{{cite web |author=Mark Murray |title=VA GOPers Get Joe Wilson's Help |url=http://firstread.msnbc.msn.com/archive/2009/09/23/2078612.aspx |work=First Read |publisher=msnbc.com |date=September 23, 2009 |accessdate=September 28, 2009}}</ref> and the [[National Republican Congressional Committee]].<ref>{{cite web |author=Mark Murray |title=Joe Wilson, GOP Celebrity? |url=http://firstread.msnbc.msn.com/archive/2009/09/25/2080351.aspx |work=First Read |publisher=msnbc.com |date=September 25, 2009 |accessdate=September 28, 2009}}</ref> Political observers described him as a \"GOP fundraising star.\"<ref>{{cite web |author=Alex Koppelman |title=Joe Wilson turns GOP fundraising star |url=http://www.salon.com/politics/war_room/2009/09/25/wilson_email/index.html |work=Salon |publisher= |date=September 25, 2009 |accessdate=September 28, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Joe Wilson Becomes GOP Fundraising Star |url=http://www.myfoxdc.com/dpp/news/092509_joe_wilson_becomes_gop_fundraising_star |agency=Associated Press |publisher=myfoxdc.com |date=September 25, 2009 |accessdate=October 1, 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Other controversies===\nOn a 2002 live broadcast of the [[C-SPAN]] talk show ''[[Washington Journal]]'', guests Wilson and Democratic congressman [[Bob Filner]] were discussing [[Iraq]]i [[weapons of mass destruction]]. When Filner noted that the US provided Iraq with \"chemical and biological weapons\" in the 1980s, Wilson incorrectly stated that this idea was \"made up\" and commented to Filner, \"This hatred of America by some people is just outrageous. And you need to get over that.\" Wilson apologized for his remarks in statements to the press.<ref>\"Wilson accuses California congressman of hating America\", [[Associated Press]], September 26, 2002</ref><ref>[[Lloyd Grove]], \"The Reliable Source\", ''[[Washington Post]]'', September 25, 2002</ref>\n\nIn 2003, [[Essie Mae Washington-Williams]] revealed that she was the daughter of Wilson's former employer, the late Senator [[Strom Thurmond]], and Thurmond's black maid. Wilson was among those who publicly doubted her assertion that Thurmond had a child [[out of wedlock]]. Wilson said even if her story was true, she should not have revealed it because \"it's a [[Smear campaign|smear]]\" on Thurmond's image and was a way to \"diminish\" Thurmond's legacy.<ref>Jennifer Talhelm, \"Most Say Revelation Won't Alter Thurmond's Legacy\", ''[[The State (newspaper)|The State]]'', December 14, 2003</ref> After Thurmond's family acknowledged the truth of Washington-Williams' revelation, Wilson apologized, but said that he still thought that she should not have revealed that Thurmond was her father.<ref>Jennifer Talhelm and Aaron Gould Shinin, \"Critics of Thurmond's Daughter Change Tune\", ''[[The State (newspaper)|The State]]'', December 19, 2003</ref>\n\nIn November 2009, the [[New York Times]] reported that Joe Wilson and [[Blaine Luetkemeyer]] made identical written statements, saying that \"One of the reasons I have long supported the U.S. biotechnology industry is that it is a homegrown success story that has been an engine of job creation in this country. Unfortunately, many of the largest companies that would seek to enter the biosimilar market have made their money by outsourcing their research to foreign countries like India.\" The statement was originally drafted by lobbyists for [[Genentech]], now a Swiss [[biotechnology]] firm, but originally founded, and still headquartered in South San Francisco, CA.<ref>{{cite news | first=Robert | last=Pear | title=In House, Many Spoke With One Voice \u2013 Lobbyists' | date=November 14, 2009 | url =http://www.nytimes.com/2009/11/15/us/politics/15health.html | work =The New York Times | accessdate = November 24, 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Political campaigns==\nWilson was elected in 2001 in a special election caused by the death of Spence, his former boss. Wilson once said that a dying Spence called him from his hospital bed and asked him to run.<ref>Philip Rucker and Ann Gerhart, [http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/09/10/AR2009091002051_pf.html \"The Gentlemen From South Carolina: State Has a History of Rowdy Politics\"], ''[[Washington Post]]'', September 11, 2009</ref> In a crowded five-way Republican primary--the real contest in this heavily Republican district--Wilson tallied 75 percent of the vote, more than enough to win the nomination outright.  He prevailed in the December 18 special election with 73 percent of the vote.<ref name=\"AP\">[http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/external/pre-election/state_districts/SC.html?SITE=NCGRDELN&SECTION=POLITICS&TEMPLATE=DEFAULT AP.org web site]. Retrieved April 10, 2008.</ref><ref name=\"sc_specialelection2001\">Special election vote totals are at [http://www.scvotes.org/statistics/election_returns_from_primaries_and_general_elections_statewide South Carolina Election Commission official web site; go to the page for December 18, 2001 special election]. Retrieved April 10, 2008.</ref>  Wilson won election to a full term in 2002 with 84 percent of the vote, facing four minor-party candidates.<ref name=\"AP\" /><ref>He received 144,149 votes to 17,189 and 9,650 minor party candidates with 371 write-in votes. See [http://www.scvotes.org/statistics/election_returns_from_primaries_and_general_elections_statewide South Carolina Election Commission official web site, go to the page for November 5, 2002 general election]. Retrieved April 10, 2008.</ref>\n\nWilson was mentioned as a possible candidate for retiring Senator [[Ernest Hollings|Fritz Hollings]]' seat in 2004,<ref>Chris Cillizza {{Wayback |date=20040815093544 |url=http://www.schotline.com/rollcall0819003.htm |title=S.C. Getting Nasty Early}}. ''Roll Call''. August 18, 2003</ref> but he decided to run for a second full term and beat his opponents, [[United States Democratic Party|Democrat]] [[Michael Ellisor]] and [[Constitution Party (United States)|Constitution Party]] nominee [[Steve Lefemine]], with 65 percent of the vote.<ref name=\"AP\" /><ref>Wilson got 181,862 votes to 93,249 for Democrat Ellisor, and 4,447 for minor party candidate Lefemine, with 312 write-ins. See [http://www.scvotes.org/statistics/election_returns_from_primaries_and_general_elections_statewide South Carolina Election Commission official web site, go to the page for November 2, 2004 general election]. Retrieved April 10, 2008.</ref> \n\n===2008===\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in South Carolina, 2008#District 2}}\nWilson won re-election in November 2008, defeating the Democratic nominee, Iraq War veteran [[Rob Miller (South Carolina politician)|Rob Miller]], 54% to 46%.  It was the closest race in the district in 20 years, and the closest race that Wilson had ever faced in 24 years as an elected official.  He only survived by winning his native Lexington County by 33,000 votes, more than the overall margin of 26,000 votes.  \n\n===2010===\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in South Carolina, 2010#District 2}}\nChallenged by Democratic nominee Rob Miller, Libertarian nominee Eddie McCain, and Constitution Party nominee Marc Beaman,<ref>[http://www.scvotes.org/files/2010%20GE%20Candidate%20Names%20by%20Office%20and%20Party%20Report.pdf Official candidate list] SC Secretary of State</ref> Wilson won re-election on November 2, 2010, defeating Miller 53% to 44%.\n<!--  commenting out section unrelated to elections, and, unsourced.\n===2011===\nIn 2011, Wilson was vindicated when Department of Health and Human Services spokesmen confirmed $8.5 million of \"Affordable Health Care\" grant money will go to centers serving migrant and seasonal farm workers, saying patients will not be asked about immigration status. The centers will offer primary care to all who come in (regardless of ability to pay or immigration status).\n\n\u201cIt is clearly providing money that should be going to American citizens to illegal immigrants,\u201d Wilson said. \u201cIt\u2019s even worse than I thought. They won\u2019t even ask for status.\u201d\n\nOn his campaign website, Wilson wrote: \u201cIt is inevitable that they will serve illegal aliens. The president specifically promised the American people that \u2018Obamacare\u2019 would not cover those who are here illegally. He misled all of us.\u201d -->\n\n===2012===\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in South Carolina, 2012}}\nIn the November 2012 general election, Joe Wilson ran unopposed and was re-elected with 96% of the vote.\n\n==Electoral history==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0.5em ; font-size:95%\"\n|+ {{ushr|South Carolina|2|}}: Results 2000\u20132014